                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I think a lot of people who are currently saying they will not play EQ2 will infact change their minds once the game is out and continues to get raving reviews and slowly some of the friends poor over into what will become the next generation of MMORPGs. Cross game tells between EQ1 and EQ2 will make the transition easy at first and when the people in EQ1 get messages from friends in EQ2 like "WOW this is amazing, i cant believe this dungeon its freaky! even better then when i first start EQ1" etc..  I think the draw will become even stronger.
<br />

<br />
People who say they have "too much time invested" in EQ1 is their reason for not switching, are really thinking kind of short sighted. EQ2 is a different game then EQ1 just as WoW and CoH and others are different then EQ1. EQ2 will have some slight similarities to allow people to feel its still "Everquest" but for the most part its a different game. Will the people never play another game as long as they live? at some point they will leave EQ1, or EQ1 will close down. At some point wether by their choice or not they WILL leave EQ1 and time investment doesnt have anything to do with it. Now if they still have things to accomplish in EQ1 then thats fine, but thats why SoE offers the excellent SoE ALL access pass that lets you play EQ1 and EQ2 and others for one cheap price, thats a real deal in my opinion and should allow even silly people to try both games out =)
<br />

<br />
As for the people who think WoW is going to be so great, I have to wonder if they have completely researched the features that WoW is including compared to what EQ2 has to offer. Im not against WoW, infact ill give it a shot aswell just so I can make informed opinions, however by feature lists alone EQ2 is definately the greater game. WoWs graphical style may appeal to some and thats fine, but the graphics of EQ2 push the limits of technology and definately take the genre a step forward regardless of your opinion on the issue. I think the most important points in the comparison between EQ2 and WoW is some of the very poor and possibily game breaking features that WoW has already included, for example:
<br />

<br />
A 24 hour clock, so that when its night out for you, it will be night in WoW. While this sounds like a great idea at first, it is not really well thought out. When you get home from work at night, it will be night in WoW, you will never get to see the daylight of WoW, or the sun rise etc.. you will always be playing at night if that is your allotted game time in real life. 
<br />

<br />
The fact that there are two opposing factions allows for great story line, EQ2 has this aswell, where the games differ however is that WoW while trying to take a more "RP" standpoint does NOT allow you to group with members of the opposing faction. What this means in the end is that you cannot play with your friends at all if they choose any of the 4 races on the opposite side that you do. Entire guilds will be broken apart, because I do not see everyone choosing the same side, each will have something they wish to play. In addition, this means that if you DO want to play with your friends you now only have *4* races to choose from since you cannot be of the opposite faction. That is an extremely poor amount of choices for an MMORPG.
<br />

<br />
Then we come to the rather recent feature WoW announced called the "Rest State" system. This means that the longer you are online playing your character in WoW the more tired your character becomes, the more tired he becomes the less XP you earn from killing monsters. While this may not effect some people as much as others in the way of limiting their game time (who will play their main character eventually gaining only 1/8th the amount of xp?), it still sets a bad precedant for MMORPGs. We pay a set amount of money each month to play for as long as we want according to our schedule and NOT the game companies. That is basically the current standard for mmorpgs, the rest state system adds a mechanic that allows the company to essentially "set your play time" according to their standard. Blizzards moto in the past has always been "Is it fun?" thats how they determin if a game is ready for shipping, if a feature should be added, etc.. unfortunately blizzard has forgot their rule on this feature, as it adds nothing fun, but only limits and sets a bad precedant for future mmorpgs. I want to play when *I* want, and i want to play how *I* want, we need to keep the power in our hands.
<br />

<br />
While this next one may not be a big deciding factor for most people, it is however something that bothers me. Trade skills in WoW are linked directly to character leveling. Therefore you cannot become a master weapons smith unless you also are a level 60 Warlock (for example). In EQ2 however, you have more choice, you can be a level 2 Warlock, and a level 40 Weapon Smith, or a level 40 Warlock and a level 2 Weapon Smith. In MMORPGs a lot of fun is provided by choices, character customization, etc.. Players want individuality and the character creation in WoW is lacking severely in any form of individuality, while in EQ2 you have a level of character customization that is unheard of in MMORPGs to date (with only CoH coming close). You WILL look unique in EQ2, you will NOT look unique in WoW.
<br />

<br />
If you add in blizzards famous reputation for having the most immature game audience in the industry (battle.net kiddies as they call them) and their history of games that are hacked continously while you wait a very long time for lengthy patches to try and stop them which never does, you may not want to just jump on the WoW bandwagon just yet, hype is not everything and while WoW will certainly set records for opening day sales, lonegity is the real prize for an MMORPG. If diablo is any glimpse of the play style WoW will have, then you might be zooming through content and leveling quicker then even the casual gamer would appreciate. 
<br />

<br />
For me, its EQ2, I will try WoW, but currently the feature list of both games means there isnt any reason to assume that WoW will be better excluding company reputation for previous good titles of course.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
