                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">To stand on the other side of the fence for a moment...... and rebutt a few of Sorvinis' points as I see them.
<br />

<br />
Firstly reviews are by and large a load of crap. I have yet to find a decent review that wasn't essentially a marketing pitch and choose not to believe them. Basically video gaming magazines and sites have to make agreements with the gaming companies to promote the product so they can gain exclusive cheats, images, information, beta keys and guides which help sell the site/magazine. This represents a pretty significant conflict of interest and that's why we so seldomly see poor reviews of any major companies product. Moreso the staff are often fanboi-z themselves which skew reviews even more. Good review are hardly convincing, and WoW is getting them too.
<br />

<br />
As for Everquest pushing the technological limits that's fine if you have a higher end computer, however Blizzard has always made a commitment to making games that are playable on older systems to try and appeal to the largest playerbas possible. If graphics are important to you I will concede that EQ2 is certainly more lifelike, however the art in WoW is top of the line. Personally I really didn't enjoy having to upgrade my computer so frequently to play EQ. I remember my friends buying me several upgrades so I could play with them when velious came out and my computer couldn't handle it. When Luclin came out I had to upgrade my RAM. When PoP came out I had to upgrade my processor/motherboard - for the second time. Thankfully I have generous friends who were willing to help me out, but I know alot of my friends don't and couldn't play EQ with me as a result. 
<br />

<br />
WoW is still in beta and many of the items you listed are still currenty under heavy scrutiny. The rest system and tradeskills in particular are being reviewed constantly by the development team and alot of feedback is still coming in on those items. The 24 hour clock has been discussed, but it's definitely not a top priority for the development team since it's a rather minor issue. I realize with EQ it's pretty easy to tell what the final product is going to look like because they really rush the testing phase, but Blizzard has continually had long testing/development cycles and the end product rarely looks like it does in early Beta unlike EQ's proven track record of half finished content. Even the idea of being able to group with either faction has been discussed and offering servers with complete Horde/Allience grouping as a ruleset has been listed as a possibility. It's really easy to point out the flaws in a product that's not even close to being released.
<br />

<br />
As for the reputation of the playerbase I for one came to EQ from Starcracft, in fact the first guild I joined in EQ was Four Elements on Xev which was also the Starcraft clan I was a member of. I too found the population of Battlenet to be a significantly different one from EQ, and I noticed a rather interesting trend. the bNet-Kiddies never made it past level 30. They'd move on generally because the game requires social interaction to advance and they had smeared their reputation, their parents felt it was taking too much of their time and cancelled there account, of they got bored because they couldn't PK anyone and moved to   a Zek server or just quit all together. Fully expect the same to happen in WoW.
<br />

<br />
Moreso alot of EQ players will be moving to WoW and will form a significant portion of the playerbase, as well as players from other MMORPGs. Avoiding the BNet kiddies is a breeze although much like the early days of EQ you can expect bad apples to show up periodicaly.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />e^(i*Pi) + 1 = 0</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
	<tr>
