                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I think you have some fair points in your post twizle, its true both games are in beta testing at the moment and things that are very poorly implimented (like many of the things i mentioned in wow) may totaly change. 
<br />

<br />
The point of making my original post was however to show that there is really no reason to believe that WoW is simply going to clean house, it has MANY negative points about it just like other MMORPGs. 
<br />

<br />
I personally find the WoW hype to be currently undeserving, not because its a bad game, infact its not a bad game so far, but because people are acting like its the second coming. A game thats made by a good company 6 years after EQ1 had better seem great, but what some people dont realize is that EQ2 is in that same boat WoW is in. People compare WoW to EQ1 and say "WoW is the best!" meanwhile they havent played WoWs competition EQ2 or Vanguard. All these games have come 6 years after EQ1 and any of them will most likely seem "the best" comparitively, but no one should say such things until they have played another MMORPG from that new generation to compare it properly. Its like comparing Gamecube to original Nintendo, of course it looks amazing, you should be comparing it to Playstation 2 instead.
<br />

<br />
As for the system requirements issue. EQ2 requirements arent really anything special: 1ghz processor 512 ram and a 64 meg video card 9x compatible. That is a pretty sub standard machine for gamers now days, let alone in the years to come. I appreciate that EQ2 allows low end users like mentioned above to play, while at the same time allowing people to crank options up and play the game on high end machines that people might upgrade too in a few years. They have the future in mind, and I like that idea rather then the game looking dated 6 months after its released. The price of a machine with the minimum requirements for EQ2 now days would probably be around $300 or less, and if people have a machine less then 1ghz, then they probably should think about upgrading anyway. Cars require maintenance and so do computers, imho =)
<br />

<br />
Your probably correct about some review sites, and im sure people catch on to which sites sell out like you suggested. I dont think I would write all reviewer sites off as sell out advertisers though, I know some people who work for various gaming sites and they are people with good journalistic integrity. Still one thing is true, they ARE just opinions in the end, however they are usually more informed then us "onlookers".</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
